WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.550 --> 00:00:03.070
DAN GALPIN: So I
wanted to begin.

00:00:03.070 --> 00:00:06.310
My job is basically to be awake
this early in the morning.

00:00:06.310 --> 00:00:09.550
I'm usually very funny when
I haven't had much sleep.

00:00:09.550 --> 00:00:12.490
And this is always an
exciting week, the week of IO.

00:00:12.490 --> 00:00:16.155
So I actually wrote
my name in the notes,

00:00:16.155 --> 00:00:17.530
just so I'd remember
to say them.

00:00:17.530 --> 00:00:19.930
Because this is
usually a time when

00:00:19.930 --> 00:00:22.330
we're just running around,
trying to get everything

00:00:22.330 --> 00:00:24.160
ready for tomorrow.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.050
And this is always a
really fun thing to do,

00:00:26.050 --> 00:00:27.740
to meet with you guys today.

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:32.210
And so I'm really excited
that Bill asked me to be here.

00:00:32.210 --> 00:00:34.250
I've been doing this
for a really long time.

00:00:34.250 --> 00:00:36.670
I've been working to make
Android development better,

00:00:36.670 --> 00:00:39.940
delivering some modestly
memorable presentations,

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:42.520
and occasionally, maybe more
memorable looks over the years.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:44.228
I particularly like
the Jean Valjean look

00:00:44.228 --> 00:00:48.492
I have on the left, over there.

00:00:48.492 --> 00:00:50.950
So the first thing I like to
do is summarize all the things

00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:54.210
that I thought were cool
about the day we had at GDC.

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:56.050
And so how many people,
by a show of hands,

00:00:56.050 --> 00:00:59.095
actually attended and saw
all of our GDC sessions?

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:03.290
All right.

00:01:03.290 --> 00:01:05.325
Well, that's usually
about what I expected.

00:01:05.325 --> 00:01:06.200
That's why I do this.

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:11.270
And I grouped these to
kind of help myself.

00:01:11.270 --> 00:01:13.040
So we talked about
a lot of things

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:14.820
about what Google Play is doing.

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:17.570
So I'll put my
Google Play hat on.

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:19.940
We mentioned that in
the last 12 months,

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:22.550
the number of Android users
who installed a game more than

00:01:22.550 --> 00:01:24.260
doubled, compared to
the previous year,

00:01:24.260 --> 00:01:26.660
and 40% of that growth is
coming from these emerging

00:01:26.660 --> 00:01:32.180
markets, such as Brazil,
India, Indonesia, and Mexico.

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:35.000
We recognize that because
about half of mobile gamers

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.120
are women we kicked off
an initiative to celebrate

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:40.910
and empower women as
players and creators.

00:01:40.910 --> 00:01:43.220
We did a lot of stuff
inside the store

00:01:43.220 --> 00:01:46.990
to actually improve the
way that people find games.

00:01:46.990 --> 00:01:49.874
We improved search on
play with personalization,

00:01:49.874 --> 00:01:51.290
such as the search
refinements you

00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:55.981
see on the left and
recommendations on the right.

00:01:55.981 --> 00:01:56.480
Nice!

00:02:01.010 --> 00:02:04.760
That is because I'm
running a dev version.

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:08.632
I swear, hilarious.

00:02:08.632 --> 00:02:10.340
This is what happens
when you have to run

00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:12.812
the unstable version of Chrome.

00:02:12.812 --> 00:02:14.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:15.860
All right.

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:19.100
I have no idea what's
going to happen there.

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:20.075
That was pretty cool.

00:02:23.590 --> 00:02:26.200
This is why live
presentations are really fun.

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:30.810
I am going to try
to kill everything

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:31.686
that's not important.

00:02:31.686 --> 00:02:33.310
And I'm hoping that
won't happen again.

00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:35.910
But, if it does,
we'll roll with it.

00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:37.125
All right, let's go back.

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:41.490
I thought this would be so cool!

00:02:41.490 --> 00:02:43.280
I did this last year
on my Chromebook

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:47.340
running the latest version,
but this is just, uh--

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:49.430
all right.

00:02:49.430 --> 00:02:52.060
Let me pull that off
and start over again.

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:52.560
Where was I?

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:55.060
I was talking about something
about Google Play, I remember.

00:02:57.120 --> 00:02:58.680
AUDIENCE: You said
better search.

00:02:58.680 --> 00:03:00.610
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, better search.

00:03:00.610 --> 00:03:04.700
We had-- let me try
this one more time.

00:03:04.700 --> 00:03:07.630
That's amazing.

00:03:07.630 --> 00:03:10.360
Thank you all for
putting up with me.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:13.570
And this-- real fun.

00:03:13.570 --> 00:03:15.190
Maybe next time I'll actually--

00:03:15.190 --> 00:03:16.620
oh, no!

00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:20.680
Now it's all-- this
is turned back on?

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:21.765
All right, that's OK.

00:03:21.765 --> 00:03:22.920
AUDIENCE: You want
to switch to this?

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:23.670
DAN GALPIN: Yeah,
maybe I should--

00:03:23.670 --> 00:03:25.590
Joe, why don't you put
it up on the laptop.

00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:27.630
We'll switch over once I--

00:03:27.630 --> 00:03:28.680
give me two seconds here.

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:29.050
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, sure.

